Swing is designed/optimized  to display/paint components in 2 dimensions. The vast majority of layout managers will make sure that the components don&#39;t overlap. 

This means that you can&#39;t use a layout manager on your layered pane (if you want the components to overlap). Instead, you must manually set the size/location of components on each layer.

When you use a JLayeredPane the painting of components on each layer is managed so that the higher layer is painted last.

So your code might be changed to something like:

    import java.awt.*;
